{{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}} [[File:Canterbury earthquake memorial opening 099.jpg|thumb|The inscription for Giles on the [[Canterbury Earthquake National Memorial]]]] '''Joanne May Giles'''<ref name="14 more victims" /> (29 November 1950 – 22 February 2011) was a New Zealand television presenter and former representative sportswoman. She represented the country in [[Shooting sport|pistol shooting]] at the 1997 Oceanian Championships in [[Adelaide]], and the 2000 [[ISSF World Cup|World Cup]] in Sydney.<ref>[http://www.issf-sports.org/results.ashx ISSF – International Shooting Sport Federation > Results]</ref> She was one of New Zealand's first woman jockeys, and competed in motorsport and Rock 'n Roll competitions.<ref name="Stuff.co.nz_4699739">{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/christchurch-earthquake/quake-victims/4699739 |title=Jo Giles |date=24 February 2011 |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |accessdate=6 October 2011}}</ref><ref name="NZ_Herald_3541362">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=3541362 |title=Racing: Stable cheered as treble earns bonus |date=29 December 2003 |agency=[[NZPA]] |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=6 October 2011}}</ref>
Jo Giles was a candidate for [[ACT New Zealand]] in the [[New Zealand general election, 2005|2005 general election]].<ref name="2005 election Ilam">{{cite web |title=Official Count Results -- Ilam |url=http://2005.electionresults.govt.nz/electionresults_2005/electorate-19.html |publisher=Chief Electoral Office, Wellington |accessdate=20 November 2011 |date=1 October 2005 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523075203/http://2005.electionresults.govt.nz/electionresults_2005/electorate-19.html |archivedate=23 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She formed a local body political party "Christchurch City Vision" and was a mayoral candidate in the [[Christchurch mayoral election, 2007|2007 Christchurch local body election]].<ref name="NZH">[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/christchurch-earthquake-victims/news/article.cfm?c_id=1503038&objectid=10708385 In memory of the victims of the Christchurch earthquake: Jo Giles] NZ Herald, 24 February 2011 {{dead link|date=March 2011}}</ref> With 14,454 votes, Giles came third after [[Bob Parker (mayor)|Bob Parker]] (47,033 votes) and [[Megan Woods]] (32,821 votes) in the election contested by ten candidates.<ref>{{cite web|title=Christchurch City Mayor|url=http://www.elections2010.co.nz/2007/elections/christchurch-city-mayor|publisher=Local Elections 2010|accessdate=14 October 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100827073353/http://www.elections2010.co.nz/2007/elections/christchurch-city-mayor|archivedate=27 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
Jo Giles was later a TV presenter for the regional broadcaster [[Canterbury Television]] (CTV), with her programme "Shopping with Jo".
On 11 March 2011 police confirmed that she was one of the victims of the February [[2011 Christchurch earthquake]] in the [[CTV Building]].<ref name="14 more victims">{{cite news|title=Christchurch police name 14 more earthquake victims|url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/christchurch-earthquake/4758247/Christchurch-police-name-14-more-earthquake-victims |accessdate=15 May 2011|newspaper=The Press|date=11 March 2011}}</ref> She had four children; Anna, Sam, Liv and James.<ref name="Stuff.co.nz_4699739"/>
